body:
I was working on a mini-kernel (https://github.com/krzysz00/rust-kernel/) when I found that libcore (which, according to the documentation, is dependency-free and freestanding) unavoidable depends on libm.

I compiled the following code by `rustc lib.rs [linker flag for rlibc]; ld libtest.a`

``` rust
#![feature(no_std,lang_items,asm,core)]
#![no_std]

#![crate_type="staticlib"]
#![crate_name="test"]

#[macro_use]
extern crate core;

extern crate rlibc;

#[inline(never)]
fn mod_by(divisor: u32) -> u32 {
    return 14 % divisor;
}

#[lang="start"]
#[no_mangle]
pub fn _start() -> u32 {
    let ret = mod_by(7);
    ret
}

#[lang = "stack_exhausted"] extern fn stack_exhausted() {}
#[lang = "eh_personality"] extern fn eh_personality() {}
#[lang = "panic_fmt"] fn panic_fmt() -> ! { loop {} }
```

I expected the code to compile cleanly and run, or for there to be some form of `no_floats` directive that would remove dependencies on `libm`.

The code instead threw a large number of linker errors related to a lack of floating-point functions. 
